{
  "answer": "The patriotic anthem is **Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet** (\"National Anthem of Hindustani Children\"), chapter 26 of *Bang-E-Dara Part 1* by Allama Iqbal. It is structured in four stanzas (each rendered as a verse paragraph), each ending with the refrain declaring \"This is my homeland, this land of mine,\" and celebrates Hindustan (India) as the sacred land tying together the described figures and events.[^1]\n\n**Opening quatrain:**\n\n> Where Chishti first Truth's holy call conveyed,[^2]  \n> And Nanak's song of Oneness was displayed,[^2]  \n> The land the Tatars for their homeland made,[^2]  \n> Which drew Hijaz's sons from desert shade,[^2]\n\n**Closing quatrain:**\n\n> Its people Moses, and its peaks are Sinai's height,[^3]  \n> Where Prophet Noah's ark first saw the light,[^3]  \n> Whose very ground is a stair to heaven's light,[^3]  \n> To live here is a paradise of pure delight,[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, chapter 26: [Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/26-hindustani-bachon-ka-qaumi-geet/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, chapter 26, [p-da6786](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/26-hindustani-bachon-ka-qaumi-geet/translation/#p-da6786).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, chapter 26, [p-a9f72d](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/26-hindustani-bachon-ka-qaumi-geet/translation/#p-a9f72d).",
